<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900830-0072</DOCNO><DOCID>900830-0072.</DOCID><HL>   Kansas City Power   Is Seeking Talks With   Kansas Gas andamp; Electric</HL><DATE>08/30/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   KLT KGE</CO><IN>TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)GAS UTILITIES (GAS)</IN><LP>   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Kansas City Power andamp; Light Co. urgedKansas Gas andamp; Electric Co. to meet with its officials beforeentering talks with any other potential buyers.   Kansas City Pandamp;L last month launched an unsolicited$27-a-share, or $857 million, tender offer for the Wichitautility. But Kansas Gandamp;E rebuffed the offer as inadequate andoverly conditional, saying also that the bid &quot;raisessubstantial and serious legal questions and numerousuncertainties under state and federal statutes.&quot;</LP><TEXT>   Earlier this week, Kansas Gandamp;E disclosed in a Securitiesand Exchange filing that it might consider a merger orrecapitalization plan as a means of foiling its unwantedsuitor.   In a letter made public yesterday, Kansas City Pandamp;LPresident and Chief Executive Officer Drue Jennings toldKansas Gandamp;E Chairman and President Wilson K. Cadman: &quot;We areconcerned that KGandamp;E's statement indicates that you may enterdiscussions with third parties without also engaging indiscussions with us.&quot;   Mr. Jennings urged: &quot;Let's meet before you take any steps,such as agreeing to substantial commitment and other fees oragreeing to merge with, or sell significant assets to, athird party.&quot;   Kansas City Pandamp;L's offer has been extended until Sept. 14;at the time the original expired Aug. 20, about 43% of KansasGandamp;E's common shares had been tendered.</TEXT></DOC>